00:37:38.075 --> 00:37:39.700
SPEAKER: I wanted to
ask you as a fan--

00:37:39.700 --> 00:37:41.530
so what did you tell to David--

00:37:41.530 --> 00:37:44.720
there was a picture when he was
smoking a cigarette-- fantastic

00:37:44.720 --> 00:37:45.220
picture.

00:37:45.220 --> 00:37:47.620
What exactly were
your words, you know,

00:37:47.620 --> 00:37:50.544
right before this moment when
he was having the cigarette?

00:37:50.544 --> 00:37:52.460
What-- how do you work
with these celebrities?

00:37:52.460 --> 00:37:54.826
Because you're a fan,
as well, I assume?

00:37:54.826 --> 00:37:56.200
SERGEI SARAKHANOV:
I was shooting

00:37:56.200 --> 00:38:01.960
David Lynch in Kiev, when he
came with this foundation,

00:38:01.960 --> 00:38:05.210
the David Lynch Foundation.

00:38:05.210 --> 00:38:06.880
You know, this
foundation is working

00:38:06.880 --> 00:38:09.940
on transcendental meditation.

00:38:09.940 --> 00:38:13.900
Last 20 years, David Lynch
working on not only cinema,

00:38:13.900 --> 00:38:15.804
on meditation--

00:38:15.804 --> 00:38:16.720
and writing the books.

00:38:16.720 --> 00:38:18.500
Maybe somebody has read it.

00:38:18.500 --> 00:38:23.660
So David came with a visit
of his foundation openings--

00:38:23.660 --> 00:38:26.140
opening the part
of it in Ukraine.

00:38:26.140 --> 00:38:33.100
And I got a booking for me to
make some portraits of him.

00:38:33.100 --> 00:38:36.190
For first time, it
sounds very good.

00:38:36.190 --> 00:38:40.810
I must have one
shooting for 15 minutes,

00:38:40.810 --> 00:38:43.494
and the second shooting
for half an hour.

00:38:43.494 --> 00:38:45.160
And that just became
a little bit crazy,

00:38:45.160 --> 00:38:47.400
because such a
legend, for me, is--

00:38:47.400 --> 00:38:48.580
for such time.

00:38:48.580 --> 00:38:54.940
But as a result, I had two
shootings for four minutes,

00:38:54.940 --> 00:38:56.680
every [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:56.680 --> 00:38:58.030
It was a little bit crazy.

00:38:58.030 --> 00:39:00.110
For the first day, I
became really crazy.

00:39:00.110 --> 00:39:03.250
And after the shooting,
I just laid to the floor

00:39:03.250 --> 00:39:08.030
and tried to breathe, because
I just became very nervous.

00:39:08.030 --> 00:39:10.690
But I get ready
for the shooting.

00:39:10.690 --> 00:39:13.090
It was in this cinema theater.

00:39:13.090 --> 00:39:15.550
I brought there,
with my assistants,

00:39:15.550 --> 00:39:20.180
a small studio with a blue
background, and lighting,

00:39:20.180 --> 00:39:22.060
and so on.

00:39:22.060 --> 00:39:25.900
And when I see him, I understood
that he's very tired, now.

00:39:25.900 --> 00:39:29.340
Because many people--
around 25 or 30 people

00:39:29.340 --> 00:39:30.530
were running around him.

00:39:30.530 --> 00:39:32.500
The agents, the PR
directors, there

00:39:32.500 --> 00:39:35.500
are some guys from
the foundation.

00:39:35.500 --> 00:39:38.230
And he had elections,
he had many meetings.

00:39:38.230 --> 00:39:41.890
So I just looked at him,
and he looked at me,

00:39:41.890 --> 00:39:45.340
and I understood that this is
a legend, but for this moment,

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:47.810
it's a very tired legend.

00:39:47.810 --> 00:39:51.850
And I don't want to make
some violate shooting on him.

00:39:51.850 --> 00:39:54.770
So I know that he
loves to smoke.

00:39:54.770 --> 00:40:00.130
And I said, David, just
sit and smoke for a bit.

00:40:00.130 --> 00:40:02.650
Don't think about me, now.

00:40:02.650 --> 00:40:05.150
I will just shoot
you from the side.

00:40:05.150 --> 00:40:06.790
So I put the lighting.

00:40:06.790 --> 00:40:10.501
And I gave two minutes,
maybe, of my four minutes.

00:40:10.501 --> 00:40:11.000
You see?

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:11.880
Half.

00:40:11.880 --> 00:40:13.630
I just gave it for this moment.

00:40:13.630 --> 00:40:17.720
Because I wanted him
to be more comfortable.

00:40:17.720 --> 00:40:21.550
And then I asked him to
come to the blue background.

00:40:21.550 --> 00:40:24.580
And he said, OK,
only for two shots.

00:40:24.580 --> 00:40:26.720
And I said, David, it
will be not for two--

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:30.400
it will be maybe 15
or 20 shots, but I

00:40:30.400 --> 00:40:34.060
swear it will be
very quick, and I

00:40:34.060 --> 00:40:36.020
won't be saying to do anything.

00:40:36.020 --> 00:40:38.350
You just can stay
and stare at me,

00:40:38.350 --> 00:40:41.180
and also, you can
continue smoking.

00:40:41.180 --> 00:40:45.370
And this way, I feel some
sympathy going from him.

00:40:45.370 --> 00:40:52.660
Because he understood that I
rely on him, and I see a man.

00:40:52.660 --> 00:40:54.280
A man-- a human.

00:40:54.280 --> 00:40:57.430
Not the functional man from
cinema, not the celebrity--

00:40:57.430 --> 00:40:59.350
just a human.

00:40:59.350 --> 00:41:02.380
And it was kind of humanity.

00:41:02.380 --> 00:41:05.740
So the second shooting
was quite [INAUDIBLE],,

00:41:05.740 --> 00:41:08.430
because I had to do many shots.

00:41:08.430 --> 00:41:11.530
As in the first day,
his PR guys just

00:41:11.530 --> 00:41:14.560
cropped all of my shooting
for several minutes.

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:18.010
So I get a big set-up
from several points,

00:41:18.010 --> 00:41:21.040
shooting and testing my
light on their systems.

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:24.430
So I build some
kind of corridor.

00:41:24.430 --> 00:41:27.820
And when David came, I
told him about my idea

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:29.800
about shooting a poster
for the documentary

00:41:29.800 --> 00:41:32.020
about him coming to Ukraine.

00:41:32.020 --> 00:41:33.910
And I showed him
the locations, and I

00:41:33.910 --> 00:41:36.130
told him something
about ideas, because I

00:41:36.130 --> 00:41:39.160
know that he is a
director, and he

00:41:39.160 --> 00:41:42.500
likes when people
understand what I do now.

00:41:42.500 --> 00:41:44.300
And also, he knew me.

00:41:44.300 --> 00:41:47.770
He remembered me from
yesterday's shooting.

00:41:47.770 --> 00:41:50.300
So it was quite comfortable.

00:41:50.300 --> 00:41:53.800
And in the end, I
asked him to sit here--

00:41:53.800 --> 00:41:55.600
it's too contrast,
here, on this screen.

00:41:55.600 --> 00:41:59.590
But you can find this image on
Instagram and on the internet.

00:41:59.590 --> 00:42:03.720
So for the last moment, I asked
him to think about something.

00:42:03.720 --> 00:42:06.342
He's thinking now to
look in the window.

00:42:06.342 --> 00:42:07.800
And then, in the
last shot, I asked

00:42:07.800 --> 00:42:09.010
him to look in the camera.

00:42:09.010 --> 00:42:12.160
And here is, now,
not a tired old man--

00:42:12.160 --> 00:42:15.430
now, I think, that in this
photo, he's just quite legend.

00:42:15.430 --> 00:42:16.060
As he is.

00:42:16.060 --> 00:42:17.290
Because for me--

00:42:17.290 --> 00:42:21.844
I told you about interest,
about your thinking

00:42:21.844 --> 00:42:23.760
about the people who
you're shooting-- for me,

00:42:23.760 --> 00:42:24.580
it's a legend.

00:42:24.580 --> 00:42:28.415
For me, it's a giant part
of world cinema culture,

00:42:28.415 --> 00:42:29.620
Twin Peaks.

00:42:29.620 --> 00:42:31.390
For me, this person--
he was a friend

00:42:31.390 --> 00:42:33.950
of Andy Warhol, and many
other legendary people.

00:42:33.950 --> 00:42:36.160
So I feel this
person is legendary.

00:42:36.160 --> 00:42:38.670
And I wanted, also,
to make this portrait

00:42:38.670 --> 00:42:43.020
legendary-- with legendary, a
deep lighting, with big volume.

00:42:43.020 --> 00:42:44.020
SPEAKER: It's fantastic.

00:42:44.020 --> 00:42:44.520
Fantastic.

00:42:44.520 --> 00:42:46.290
SERGEI SARAKHANOV:
So, It's true story.

