00:43:02.640 --> 00:43:04.850
to Irish music for many years.

00:43:04.850 --> 00:43:06.320
I love Damien Rice.

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:08.340
I love Glen Hansard.

00:43:08.340 --> 00:43:11.550
I like U2.

00:43:11.550 --> 00:43:18.030
I have shot [INAUDIBLE],, as
a great musician, Irish born.

00:43:18.030 --> 00:43:22.260
So-- and I watched
Dublin in movies, also.

00:43:22.260 --> 00:43:24.030
I have seen several movies--

00:43:24.030 --> 00:43:25.680
maybe somebody has seen it--

00:43:25.680 --> 00:43:27.390
"Greenwhich Mean Time."

00:43:27.390 --> 00:43:32.130
It's a great movie about
Belfast, about Great Britain.

00:43:32.130 --> 00:43:34.230
And also some movies
about Dublin, too.

00:43:34.230 --> 00:43:39.030
So it was nice meeting,
like with some old friend,

00:43:39.030 --> 00:43:40.600
when I came here.

00:43:40.600 --> 00:43:43.620
And also, I'm a
Norse-born person,

00:43:43.620 --> 00:43:47.730
so for me, it's also kind
of a Northern country

00:43:47.730 --> 00:43:49.020
with strong people.

00:43:49.020 --> 00:43:53.110
A little bit, maybe, sometimes
bully, and something like that,

00:43:53.110 --> 00:43:55.276
but with very kind hearts.

00:43:55.276 --> 00:43:56.308
That's me, too.

00:43:56.308 --> 00:43:58.940
[LAUGHS]

00:43:58.940 --> 00:44:02.330
SPEAKER: And now, we will take
questions from the audience.

00:44:02.330 --> 00:44:03.690
Do you guys have any questions?

00:44:03.690 --> 00:44:05.773
SERGEI SARAKHANOV: Guys,
let's speak, if you want.

00:44:05.773 --> 00:44:07.635
I will be glad to
answer the questions.

00:44:07.635 --> 00:44:09.010
AUDIENCE: I just
have a question.

00:44:09.010 --> 00:44:11.400
So, with David Lynch,
you directed him.

00:44:11.400 --> 00:44:15.514
But I guess he's kind of used to
having the camera faced at him.

00:44:15.514 --> 00:44:17.310
How do you do with,
like, regular people

00:44:17.310 --> 00:44:19.250
that you have on your projects.

00:44:19.250 --> 00:44:20.276
Where is the limit?

00:44:20.276 --> 00:44:23.630
So how do you direct them,
and where do you stop?

00:44:23.630 --> 00:44:25.380
SERGEI SARAKHANOV: I'm
working with people

00:44:25.380 --> 00:44:27.120
from creative sphere.

00:44:27.120 --> 00:44:31.560
And when I see a strong author,
or person with some kind--

00:44:31.560 --> 00:44:35.880
you know-- some
tyrannic character,

00:44:35.880 --> 00:44:38.970
which some of famous
people are in such way.

00:44:38.970 --> 00:44:41.340
First of all, I'm
doing with respect.

00:44:41.340 --> 00:44:42.790
With great respect.

00:44:42.790 --> 00:44:47.130
But I'm standing myself equal.

00:44:47.130 --> 00:44:48.480
I don't go down.

00:44:48.480 --> 00:44:49.800
I don't try to dominate.

00:44:49.800 --> 00:44:52.620
I am doing with respect,
because I think that respect is

00:44:52.620 --> 00:44:55.170
a base of good relationships.

00:44:55.170 --> 00:44:59.540
And then, I'm also doing with
respect, if a person says,

00:44:59.540 --> 00:45:02.310
"sorry, but I don't want you
shoot me from the right side.

00:45:02.310 --> 00:45:04.140
My left side is better."

00:45:04.140 --> 00:45:05.700
I'm trusting people.

00:45:05.700 --> 00:45:08.290
Sometimes, I can do experiment,
and shoot from another side,

00:45:08.290 --> 00:45:08.790
too.

00:45:08.790 --> 00:45:12.840
But I want person who
I'm shooting to see

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:17.310
and understands that I am
doing it with patience,

00:45:17.310 --> 00:45:20.680
and I am listening
to him or her.

00:45:20.680 --> 00:45:22.545
I am watching him or her.

00:45:22.545 --> 00:45:27.480
Because it's human photography,
and the main value, for me,

00:45:27.480 --> 00:45:29.880
is the comfort of the
person, and feeling good

00:45:29.880 --> 00:45:30.951
on the shooting.

00:45:30.951 --> 00:45:32.604
AUDIENCE: My
question is, can you

00:45:32.604 --> 00:45:34.210
talk a bit about your process?

00:45:34.210 --> 00:45:36.447
Not maybe when you
worked for a commercial--

00:45:36.447 --> 00:45:38.530
SERGEI SARAKHANOV: That's
also a creative process.

00:45:38.530 --> 00:45:38.740
Yeah.

00:45:38.740 --> 00:45:39.240
OK.

00:45:39.240 --> 00:45:42.930
AUDIENCE: --because from, like,
dealing with different artists

00:45:42.930 --> 00:45:46.120
[INAUDIBLE] and creative people,
I've found that people tend

00:45:46.120 --> 00:45:47.070
to have--

00:45:47.070 --> 00:45:47.900
maybe there's more.

00:45:47.900 --> 00:45:51.230
But I meant two-- one,
is very structured.

00:45:51.230 --> 00:45:52.980
You have a beginning,
and you have a plan,

00:45:52.980 --> 00:45:55.760
and [INAUDIBLE]
project management.

00:45:55.760 --> 00:45:58.490
And the other one is
very, like, flow-y,

00:45:58.490 --> 00:46:00.720
where you're guided by your
intuition, and you begin,

00:46:00.720 --> 00:46:03.170
but you don't know
where it's going to end.

00:46:03.170 --> 00:46:05.760
[INAUDIBLE] know
what's going to happen.

00:46:05.760 --> 00:46:06.885
Which one is this?

00:46:06.885 --> 00:46:08.760
SERGEI SARAKHANOV: It's
a very good question.

00:46:08.760 --> 00:46:09.990
Thank you.

00:46:09.990 --> 00:46:15.840
First of all, I'm trying to find
the balance between these two

00:46:15.840 --> 00:46:17.220
polar meanings.

00:46:17.220 --> 00:46:20.000
And on the first
shooting, because I

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:23.670
love to work with people
constantly, for years--

00:46:23.670 --> 00:46:26.650
we're building
friends, relationships.

00:46:26.650 --> 00:46:28.075
And sometimes we can--

00:46:31.490 --> 00:46:33.540
don't make some
big shooting, just

00:46:33.540 --> 00:46:36.180
make as a friendly
shooting, in [INAUDIBLE]..

00:46:36.180 --> 00:46:38.390
But the first shooting is also--

00:46:38.390 --> 00:46:41.850
it's always planned
good, with references,

00:46:41.850 --> 00:46:44.110
with great location scouting.

00:46:44.110 --> 00:46:46.140
With examining the
lighting conditions,

00:46:46.140 --> 00:46:47.790
with the app I show--

00:46:47.790 --> 00:46:51.330
it's really very nice app you
should try, if you're shooting.

00:46:51.330 --> 00:46:53.300
It's good for landscape
photographers, portrait

00:46:53.300 --> 00:46:57.000
photographers, and also
street photographers, too.

00:46:57.000 --> 00:46:59.330
So first of all,
we are planning.

00:46:59.330 --> 00:47:03.210
I am doing big research, and
a big pre-production process.

00:47:03.210 --> 00:47:06.900
Because on the shooting, I
want only to shoot and speak.

00:47:06.900 --> 00:47:11.220
We speaking many, many
times-- more than shooting.

00:47:11.220 --> 00:47:14.460
The shooting coming for
two, three, or four hours.

00:47:14.460 --> 00:47:18.630
But seriously, we shoot,
I think, 20 or 25 minutes

00:47:18.630 --> 00:47:19.680
from this time.

00:47:19.680 --> 00:47:22.260
All of this time
left, we are speaking.

00:47:22.260 --> 00:47:24.120
And I speaking a lot of--

00:47:24.120 --> 00:47:27.070
I'm trying to
examine the person,

00:47:27.070 --> 00:47:28.620
and trying to
interview the person.

00:47:28.620 --> 00:47:32.400
And also, the main task for me--
not only to know the person,

00:47:32.400 --> 00:47:34.080
but to let the person know me.

00:47:34.080 --> 00:47:37.930
Because it's also
very important.

00:47:37.930 --> 00:47:40.030
And on the next
shootings, we can do it

00:47:40.030 --> 00:47:44.150
as you tell-- going with flow,
going with creative process.

00:47:44.150 --> 00:47:47.190
Many of my friends are
choreographers, dancers,

00:47:47.190 --> 00:47:51.270
painters, and such
other guys from art.

00:47:51.270 --> 00:47:52.980
So sometimes, we're doing just--

00:47:52.980 --> 00:47:54.850
we don't know what we're doing.

00:47:54.850 --> 00:47:56.850
But we-- in this
moment, we are friends.

00:47:56.850 --> 00:47:58.620
And also, we have
shooting with them when

00:47:58.620 --> 00:48:01.980
they need something special.

00:48:01.980 --> 00:48:05.670
I have to say that I'm
doing, I think, 55%

00:48:05.670 --> 00:48:08.450
of my shooting as art.

00:48:08.450 --> 00:48:13.440
I don't do it all for the money,
because I want it to be an art.

00:48:13.440 --> 00:48:16.670
And I want to take
this process--

00:48:16.670 --> 00:48:19.610
because it's all moving me.

00:48:19.610 --> 00:48:21.260
It's letting me to grow up.

00:48:21.260 --> 00:48:24.260
It lets me to know something
new, and interesting.

00:48:24.260 --> 00:48:26.840
And also, I can
speak with the person

00:48:26.840 --> 00:48:30.050
and communicate with the person
more time before shooting.

00:48:30.050 --> 00:48:32.880
I can speak one time,
but if we have time,

00:48:32.880 --> 00:48:37.310
we can just going, speaking,
shooting little bit of 35

00:48:37.310 --> 00:48:40.940
millimeter film camera, and
only after two or three weeks,

00:48:40.940 --> 00:48:44.210
start to make serious shootings.

00:48:44.210 --> 00:48:46.155
So, in this way.

00:48:46.155 --> 00:48:46.890
OK?

00:48:46.890 --> 00:48:48.858
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
in the beginning,

00:48:48.858 --> 00:48:50.830
you comment that
you would prefer

00:48:50.830 --> 00:48:53.970
five tops-- like, five top
photographers, artists,

00:48:53.970 --> 00:48:56.922
painters, movie directors,
cameraman-- like that.

00:48:56.922 --> 00:48:58.797
What are your top fives?

00:48:58.797 --> 00:48:59.630
Who is on your list?

00:48:59.630 --> 00:49:02.480
SERGEI SARAKHANOV: I will
try to tell about it.

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:07.150
I love-- I really appreciate
the work of painters, first.

00:49:07.150 --> 00:49:08.090
Yeah?

00:49:08.090 --> 00:49:10.460
It's one of Russian painters--

00:49:10.460 --> 00:49:11.480
Mikhail Vrubel.

00:49:11.480 --> 00:49:13.270
Maybe somebody know him.

00:49:13.270 --> 00:49:18.090
Also I loved the [INAUDIBLE],,
the brighter star, for me,

00:49:18.090 --> 00:49:20.540
is John Collier.

00:49:20.540 --> 00:49:21.440
It's fantastic.

00:49:21.440 --> 00:49:23.570
Sometimes, I put his
works on my desktop.

00:49:23.570 --> 00:49:26.270
I want to see it more
and more and more.

00:49:26.270 --> 00:49:29.740
Also, I like the works
of Franz Winterhalter.

00:49:29.740 --> 00:49:35.060
He is making a realistic,
great artistic portraits.

00:49:35.060 --> 00:49:37.640
They look like photos.

00:49:37.640 --> 00:49:39.080
Also, I like Rembrandt.

00:49:39.080 --> 00:49:42.890
Also, I like some classics,
like Leonardo da Vinci,

00:49:42.890 --> 00:49:43.550
Michelangelo.

00:49:43.550 --> 00:49:46.710
But I want to mention,
also, El Greco.

00:49:46.710 --> 00:49:49.940
He's making a little
bit sick paintings,

00:49:49.940 --> 00:49:52.730
but they're also
very attractive.

00:49:52.730 --> 00:49:55.700
About the cinema
directors, I would want

00:49:55.700 --> 00:50:00.080
to mention Martin McDonagh.

00:50:00.080 --> 00:50:02.450
I love him very much.

00:50:02.450 --> 00:50:04.040
Christopher Nolan.

00:50:04.040 --> 00:50:06.770
Alejandro Gonzales Inarritu.

00:50:06.770 --> 00:50:08.780
Gus van Sant.

00:50:08.780 --> 00:50:12.530
And Alfonso Cuarron,
also-- one of my favorites.

00:50:12.530 --> 00:50:16.970
About cameramen, maybe I will
not just now remember all five.

00:50:16.970 --> 00:50:21.000
But I am really impressed
by works of Chivo--

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:22.506
Emmanuel Lubezki.

00:50:22.506 --> 00:50:24.380
And we're speaking a
little bit on Instagram.

00:50:24.380 --> 00:50:25.730
It's also about
great possibilities

00:50:25.730 --> 00:50:27.500
of communication--
that I can, sometimes,

00:50:27.500 --> 00:50:31.880
communicate with I think
the most amazing cameraman

00:50:31.880 --> 00:50:32.950
in the world.

00:50:32.950 --> 00:50:35.300
He has sometimes
left in the comments.

00:50:35.300 --> 00:50:36.230
And I am just filled--

00:50:36.230 --> 00:50:38.600
[LAUGHS] What's going on?

00:50:38.600 --> 00:50:40.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:40.320 --> 00:50:43.340
And also, I love Wally Pfister.

00:50:43.340 --> 00:50:45.460
And many other guys.

00:50:45.460 --> 00:50:46.820
Rodrigo Prieto.

00:50:46.820 --> 00:50:50.720
I love, you know-- this
South American school,

00:50:50.720 --> 00:50:52.040
with a very live camera.

00:50:52.040 --> 00:50:54.560
And also, when I was
working as a cameraman

00:50:54.560 --> 00:50:59.470
on the other projects, I
also like to do live camera.

00:50:59.470 --> 00:51:03.280
Because it's giving out a
great presence as viewers.

00:51:03.280 --> 00:51:05.305
So-- that's the answer.

00:51:05.305 --> 00:51:07.180
SPEAKER: And one more
question, because we're

00:51:07.180 --> 00:51:09.824
running out of time.

00:51:09.824 --> 00:51:10.700
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:51:10.700 --> 00:51:12.316
SERGEI SARAKHANOV: Hey.

00:51:12.316 --> 00:51:15.035
AUDIENCE: So, if you
had to choose one lens

00:51:15.035 --> 00:51:16.826
and one camera that's
the most fun for you,

00:51:16.826 --> 00:51:17.742
what would you choose?

00:51:17.742 --> 00:51:19.710
And the reason I'm
asking is because it's

00:51:19.710 --> 00:51:21.130
become, like you said, easier
to take pictures today.

00:51:21.130 --> 00:51:22.510
And sometimes I leave
my camera at home.

00:51:22.510 --> 00:51:24.850
And the camera that's given
me the most joy, by far,

00:51:24.850 --> 00:51:26.990
in many years, is
the Fuji Instant.

00:51:26.990 --> 00:51:27.949
Because you only have--

00:51:27.949 --> 00:51:28.948
SERGEI SARAKHANOV: Nice.

00:51:28.948 --> 00:51:29.560
Nice, nice.

00:51:29.560 --> 00:51:31.732
AUDIENCE: Because you only
have one try, and it's--

00:51:31.732 --> 00:51:32.232
[GROANS]

00:51:32.232 --> 00:51:36.430
SERGEI SARAKHANOV: You know, I
wanted to say about Hasselblad.

00:51:36.430 --> 00:51:39.070
But you know, I will
say about the phone--

00:51:39.070 --> 00:51:44.890
it's a good end of our lecture,
because the phone gives us

00:51:44.890 --> 00:51:46.150
great possibilities.

00:51:46.150 --> 00:51:50.480
And I can shoot nice portraits,
nice landscapes, nice streets.

00:51:50.480 --> 00:51:52.510
And I don't need
to take anything.

00:51:52.510 --> 00:51:55.750
Sometimes I'm going to trip,
I'm taking only a film camera

00:51:55.750 --> 00:51:58.210
for some serious
shootings for my projects,

00:51:58.210 --> 00:51:59.950
and only an iPhone--

00:51:59.950 --> 00:52:01.510
or some kind of
Google phone, also.

00:52:01.510 --> 00:52:03.220
Pixel, Pixel 2.

00:52:03.220 --> 00:52:06.410
So-- guys, thank you a lot.

00:52:06.410 --> 00:52:09.520
It's a very big honor
for me to be here, today.

00:52:09.520 --> 00:52:13.190
I want to say, great things
to my friends who helped me

00:52:13.190 --> 00:52:14.950
to [INAUDIBLE] this text.

00:52:14.950 --> 00:52:16.520
So I have you--

00:52:16.520 --> 00:52:20.515
I want to wish you great
and good luck, and more,

00:52:20.515 --> 00:52:22.110
more photos.

00:52:22.110 --> 00:52:23.250
Thank you.

00:52:23.250 --> 00:52:26.300
[APPLAUSE]

